es to me...</span><hr size=1> What is the japanese form of the following words (that i just cant seem to figure out):<br>
<br>
To<br>
Too<br>
It<br>
Is<br>
No <br>
No Thank You<br>
<br>
And what is the proper pronounciation of &quot;Kawaii&quot;?<br>
<br>
Any/all of this info would be greatly appreciated. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=maimaipanda>maimaipanda</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Resident Panda</span><br> <font color=#336699>(4/18/03 8:45 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1097.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.sit.wisc.edu/~mamiller2/temp/pandatea.jpg height=146 width=130></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Word &quot;Too&quot; and other mysteries to me...</span><hr size=1> Hmm... .well, it's sort of difficult to translate these directly as many of them depend on the situation and context.  For instance<br>
To in the context of &quot;I give it to harry&quot; = &quot;ni&quot;<br>
To as in the context of &quot;I went to the store&quot; = &quot;he&quot;<br>
<br>
So it varies greatly.<br>
<br>
Too: usually &quot;mo&quot;<br>
<br>
It:  Another very difficult one.  It varies depending on the object, if you want to use &quot;it&quot; as a 'pronoun' or as a noun modifier, and where the object is located in relation to the speaker.  But you could go with:<br>
kore/kono - object next to speaker<br>
sore/sono - object next to listener<br>
are/ano - object away from both speaker and listener (more like &quot;that&quot;)<br>
<br>
but also &quot;it&quot; could be translated as &quot;mono&quot; (tangible objects) or &quot;koto&quot; (intangible objects).  This is a very difficult word to give a direct translation for.<br>
<br>
Is: again, varies widely on the context (and is often omitted). But you could go with &quot;ga&quot; or &quot;wa&quot; for many cases.<br>
<br>
No : ah, finally an easy one!  &quot;iie&quot;.  But of course, depending on the context, it could be translated as &quot;chigaimasu&quot; (lit. &quot;different&quot;; for example Q: &quot;are you the culprit?&quot; A: &quot;Chigaimasu!&quot; (No I'm not! (&quot;(it's a) different (person)!))<br>
<br>
<br>
No Thank You: Usually something like &quot;ii, kekko desu&quot;.  If you want to be polite, something like &quot;arigatain desukedo...&quot; (lit. &quot;I want to thank (you) but.....(I must refuse)&quot;)<br>
<br>
